Statistical significance for sales anomalies — design proposal
Status: draft, looking for feedback. Ticket: SAAI-XXX.
Background: how data flows today
Quick recap of the nightly pipeline for anyone landing here fresh.
Each night, per store, briefing_research resolves the store's like-stores from store_groups.yaml, then store_data_tap pulls sales data from Databricks. The important detail: everything we pull comes from the prod.dsr dashboard tables, which are pre-aggregated into duration buckets — "Yesterday", "WTD", "Last Week". One row per store/department/bucket. The Python side never sees individual days.
Those rows get parsed into dataclasses (store KPIs, ~12 department rows, item movers, displays, celebrations), rendered into markdown docs, and uploaded to GCS. The prompt builder then concatenates: persona + target store docs + both like-store docs into one large text prompt, sends it to Gemini via Vertex, validates the returned recommendations (department numbers are checked against the known department list), and saves everything to Postgres — runs, recommendations, actions. The store leader app reads those tables in the morning.
The problem
The model is currently the one deciding which changes are "significant", and we give it nothing to decide with.
Every number in the prompt is a point-in-time comparison — this window vs the same window last year. There's no history, no trend, no sense of how much a department normally fluctuates. So when the model sees "Produce −4.5%", it has no way to know whether Produce usually moves ±1% (in which case this is alarming) or ±6% (in which case it's a Tuesday). Whatever significance judgment it makes is invented.
Worth being honest about the current state of the codebase here: the only comparison primitive we have is growth_pct (a single TY/LY point ratio), and the only filtering anywhere is dollar floors — MATERIAL_SALES_MIN = 100.0 for movers, top-50 caps, the 80% FPP threshold. There is no mean, stddev, or z-score anywhere in either package. Meanwhile our own eval rubric already scores briefings on "Materiality — effect big enough vs normal week-to-week noise?" — so we're grading the model on a question the pipeline never computes. This proposal closes that gap.
