Produce looks bad in isolation, and today's pipeline would likely surface it. But SA08 is actually the best performer in its peer group — this is a market-wide dip, not a store problem. Flagging it wastes the leader's morning. Blooms is the opposite: +19% against a peer at −24% is a real divergence and genuinely worth a card.
A ranking driven by raw %-change gets both of these wrong. That's the whole argument in one table.
Proposal: compute significance deterministically, two tracks
The core idea is to move the significance decision out of the model and into plain math that runs before (or on) the data, then tell the model to act on the computed flag instead of judging magnitudes itself.
One framing that clarifies where the computation has to live: it depends on what we do with a failed flag. If failing the test just means "sort this lower in the feed", the test can run after generation — it's a placement algorithm. But if failing means "don't show this at all" (or "don't spend a generation slot on it"), the test has to run before generation, at the data layer — by the time the model has written about something insignificant, the slot is already spent. So:
Track A — quick win, post-generation re-ranking
After generation, we know exactly which departments the recommendations touch — each recommendation row carries validated department_number / sub_department_number columns, so this is a field read, not text parsing. For just those ~10 departments, compute significance, attach a pass/fail flag, and re-sort so failures sink to the bottom. The hook point is clean: in cron.py, the Run object sits fully formed in memory between sales_merchandising.research(...) and database.save_run(run) — the pass goes exactly there. Storage is an additive migration on recommendations (z_score, is_significant, significance_computed_at).
Cheap, ships fast, touches no prompts. Its honest limitation: it can demote noise the model wrote about, but it can never surface an anomaly the model missed. That's what Track B is for.
Track B — long-term, pre-generation at the data layer
A standalone significance computation runs nightly for all store × department rows, upstream of prompt assembly. The new fields (baseline, sigma, z_score, is_significant) ride the existing path — dataclasses → ground-truth markdown → prompt — and the persona gains an explicit rule: significance is pre-computed, only discuss flagged rows, never judge magnitude yourself. Because the flag lives in the data itself, anything downstream inherits it, including the staged pipeline work on SAAI-362 once that lands (the field names below are chosen with its numeric corpus in mind; worth a quick sync to confirm).
Once Track B runs nightly for everything, Track A's computation collapses into a lookup of already-computed flags — so these aren't two systems, just one calculation with two consumption points.
The calculation
Two complementary axes:
Cross-sectional — is this store diverging from its peers? The dsr_hist_sales_dept_dashboard_duration table already contains every store's TY/LY department sales per window, so for any department we can pull the growth distribution across the full peer set and score where the target sits. This needs no new tables and is exactly the Produce/Blooms logic above. It also has a nice property: since all peers share the same week, weather, and holidays, market-wide effects cancel out automatically.
Time-series — is this store diverging from its own history? For this we need daily-grain data (store × department × day), which does not exist in any table reachable from this repo — the dsr tables are bucket-grain, and prod.dsr is a downstream analytics copy built elsewhere. Identifying the upstream daily table is the one open dependency (see open questions). The method once we have it: a 28-day window rather than 30 (28 days = exactly four of each weekday, so the weekday mix in the window is stable), comparing same-day-of-week only — this Tuesday against the trailing 8 Tuesdays — which removes day-of-week seasonality entirely.
For both axes, robust statistics rather than plain mean/stddev:
baseline = median(comparison set)
spread   = 1.4826 × MAD           # MAD = median absolute deviation
z        = (value − baseline) / spread
Median/MAD means one freak day (or one weird peer store) can't inflate the spread and mask real anomalies. Thresholds: |z| ≥ 2.0 → significant, ≥ 3.0 → critical, all as named constants in config.py per house convention.
Edge cases we've thought through: fewer than 8 weeks of history (new or remodeled stores) → no flag, marked insufficient data, never demoted; a near-zero spread (a department that sells almost identically every day) → spread floored at a small fraction of the baseline so z can't explode; zero-sales days excluded from baselines; peers with trivial sales in a department (< $500 in the window) excluded from the cross-sectional distribution so they don't pollute it; department renames handled by keying on department number.
A quick worked example of the robust-spread property, with synthetic numbers: eight Tuesdays of Produce at 29.8, 30.4, 28.9, 31.2, 30.1, 29.5, 44.0, 30.6 (k$) — that 44.0 was a one-off event day. Median 30.25, MAD 0.65, spread ≈ 0.96. Today at 29.36 → z ≈ −0.9, not significant. With plain mean/stddev the 44.0 day would inflate σ to ~5 and hide nearly everything. Same data, honest spread.
Implementation sketch
New package store_data_tap/src/store_data_tap/significance/ following the same conventions as merch/ and fresh_ops/:
compute.py — pure math (robust_z, cross_sectional_z, classify), no I/O, fully unit-testable
queries.py — dept_peer_growth_query (existing table, works today) and a stubbed dept_daily_history_query that raises until the daily table is identified
model.py — the result dataclass / output contract:
store_id, department_number, metric, as_of_date,
actual_value, baseline_value, sigma,
z_score, is_significant, significance_tier (normal|significant|critical),
method (cross_sectional | time_series), insufficient_history, computed_at
The query runner is already generic (run(sql) takes any read-only string), which is why this is a parallel query rather than a modification of the existing builders — those hit bucket tables that can't express a time series anyway, and leaving them untouched means zero regression surface.
Track A wiring is three small pieces in briefing_research: a new significance.py with annotate_run(run, runner) (best-effort — any failure logs a warning and returns the run unchanged, so the briefing never dies because of this pass), the one-line cron hook, and the additive migration. Build order: pure math + tests first, then the cross-sectional path (no blockers), then the Track A hook, then time-series the day the table name arrives, and the render/persona changes last behind a shadow period.
Rollout
Shadow first: compute and log flags for pilot stores without changing anything user-facing, and sanity-check flag rates (at 2σ we'd expect roughly 1–2 significant departments per store per day; if every store lights up 6+, the thresholds or the peer set need another look). Then enable Track A re-ranking for pilots, tune, and only then move on to Track B's prompt changes.
Open questions
What's the upstream daily-grain sales table (store × department × day) behind the dsr dashboard aggregates? Blocks the time-series axis on both tracks; the cross-sectional axis is unaffected and can ship now.
Field naming alignment with the SAAI-362 evidence model, so the flag drops in without rework when that branch merges.
Peer set for the cross-sectional axis: all stores, a region slice, or format tier? (Affects how tight the distribution is.)
Track A UX: should failed recommendations just sink, or also render with a "routine variance" annotation?
Are the 2.0 / 3.0 thresholds global, or do inherently volatile departments (Blooms, Floral-type categories) get per-department overrides?